Vheadline
p2
VShowcasing young talent
p3
sVnews
p4
VPromising musicians who won prizes  in competitions held in connection with the Kalpathy Sangeethothsavam &#8211; 2008 showcased their talent in concerts held at Vithunni Saneeswara Temple, Palakkad.Sukanya, who won the first prize in vocal (junior) impressed listeners with her  pliable voice and dignified stage presence. Accompanied by Vighnesh Swaminathan on the violin and Balakrishnan on the mridangam, Sukanya started the concert with a Papanasam Sivan composition on Lord Ganesa, &#8216;Sreeganesa saranam,&#8217; in Thilang, set to Adi tala. Her recital included the Tamil songs &#8216;Kaliyuga varadan kankanta deivamai,&#8217; composed by Periyasami Thooran in Brindavani, Adi tala, &#8216;Ododi vanthen Kanna,&#8217;  a Ambujam Krishna composition in Dharmavathi, and &#8216;Kanthamam Kathirkamam thannil,&#8217; an eulogy on Lord Subrahmanya, the deity at Kathirkamam, in Sindhubhairavi, Adi tala.Swathi, the first prize winner in the category for violin,  entertained the rasikas with a melodious and classical exposition of  Varali. The  Dikshitar kriti  &#8216;Mamava Meenakshi,&#8217; set to Misrachappu, was adorned with cascading swaraprasthara.Visalakshi was accompanied by Viswesh on the violin and Vighnesh on the mridangam. She caught the attention of the audience with her  impressive voice and neat rendition. &#8216;Mayatheetha swaroopini,&#8217; composed by Thanjai Ponnayya, was followed by a beautiful ragalapana of Kalyani. &#8216;Himadrisuthe pahimam,&#8217; a kriti of Syama Sastri, set to Roopaka tala, was embellished with niraval and manodharmaswara at the sequence &#8216;Syamakrishna sodari.&#8217;Veena&#8217;s plus points were her  melodious and pleasant voice. She took off with an enchanting ragalapana of Shanmukhapriya for &#8216;Saravanabhava ennum thirumanthiram,&#8217; composed by Papanasam Sivan, set to Adi tala. Swati Tirunal&#8217;s &#8216;Gopalaka pahimamanisam&#8217;  was followed by delineation of  Amruthavarshini and the composition &#8216;Sudhamayi sudhanidhi. &#8216;Marivera dikkevvaro,&#8217; in Lathangi,  &#8216;Bho Sambho&#8217;  in Revathi and &#8216;Sabhapathikku veru deivam&#8217;  in Abhogi were also sung confidently.Viswesh Swaminathan&#8217;s  vibrant voice and clear padanthara created a rapport with the audience. A neat sketch of Keeravani was followed by a composition of Ramanathapuram Sreenivasa Iyer, &#8216;Nijamukharama.&#8217; It was laced with swaraprasthara.The concerts were organised by Swathi Sangeetha Sabha, Palakkad.
